2. Key Differences
1. Shape of the Distribution
Normal Distribution:

The normal distribution is symmetric around its mean, meaning the left and right sides of the distribution are mirror images.
The mean, median, and mode are all equal and occur at the same point.
It has a bell-shaped curve.
The tails extend infinitely in both directions, but the probability of extreme values diminishes rapidly.
Log-Normal Distribution:

The log-normal distribution is skewed to the right (positively skewed), meaning it has a longer tail on the right-hand side.
The mean, median, and mode are different. The mode (the most frequent value) is less than the median, which is less than the mean.
It has a right-skewed curve.
The distribution is only defined for positive values (i.e., 
𝑥
>
0
x>0) because the logarithm of a non-positive number is undefined or not real.
2. Range of Values
Normal Distribution:

The normal distribution can take any real value, from 
