4. Symmetry vs. Skewness
Normal Distribution:

It is symmetric around the mean. The left side of the distribution mirrors the right side.
There is no skewness (skewness = 0).
Log-Normal Distribution:

It is right-skewed, meaning it has a long tail on the right-hand side.
Skewness is positive, and the distribution becomes more skewed as the variance 
𝜎
2
σ 
2
  increases.
5. Additive vs. Multiplicative Processes
Normal Distribution:

The normal distribution often models additive processes, where increments or changes are added to a variable (e.g., measurement errors, natural fluctuations).
For example, height differences among individuals might be normally distributed because these differences are the result of many small additive factors (genetic, environmental, etc.).
Log-Normal Distribution:

The log-normal distribution is typically used to model multiplicative processes, where changes in a variable are proportional (i.e., grow or shrink by percentages or ratios).
For example, stock prices follow a log-normal distribution because they change multiplicatively over time (a 10% increase followed by another 10% increase is multiplicative).
6. Examples of Usage
Normal Distribution:
Height of individuals
IQ scores
Errors in measurement
SAT or GRE scores
Average daily temperature fluctuations
Log-Normal Distribution:
Stock prices
Income distribution
Duration of tasks (e.g., completion times in project management)
Sizes of living organisms or biological variables
Rainfall amounts
3. Real-World Example to Illustrate the Difference
Let’s look at stock prices and height distribution to illustrate the difference between the two distributions:

Height Distribution (Normal Distribution):
The heights of adult humans typically follow a normal distribution. For example, if the average height of a population is 170 cm with a standard deviation of 10 cm, most people will have heights clustered around 170 cm, with fewer people as you move away from that mean (either taller or shorter).
Since height can vary above and below the mean and the variations are additive (a person might be a certain number of cm taller or shorter than the average), the normal distribution models it well.
Stock Prices (Log-Normal Distribution):
Stock prices cannot be negative and usually follow a log-normal distribution. If you start with a stock price of $100, its future price could rise or fall based on percentage changes. Over time, these changes compound, so a 10% increase followed by a 10% decrease results in a net change that is not the same as adding or subtracting a fixed amount. Additionally, while prices can go up indefinitely, they are bounded below by zero, which is why the log-normal distribution is appropriate.
